To implement the `MLX90640_I2CFreqSet(int freq)` function for the STM32L476RG using the HAL library, you cannot simply pass the frequency as an integer directly to the hardware. The STM32L4 series uses a complex 32-bit timing register (`TIMINGR`) that dictates the $I^2C$ speed based on your specific clock tree.

Because calculating the `TIMINGR` value dynamically is computationally expensive, the standard practice is to pre-calculate the values for **400 kHz** and **1000 kHz (1 MHz)** using **STM32CubeMX** and swap them out.

Here is how you can implement this in your `MLX90640_I2C_Driver.cpp` file:

### 1. Get your `TIMINGR` values from CubeMX
Open STM32CubeMX and check your $I^2C$ clock source (usually PCLK1 or SYSCLK, often 80 MHz on the L476RG). 
1. Set the $I^2C$ speed to **Fast Mode (400 kHz)** and note the `Timing` value generated in the `MX_I2C1_Init` function.
2. Change the speed to **Fast Mode Plus (1000 kHz)** and note the new `Timing` value.

*(Note: The hex values below are examples assuming an 80 MHz $I^2C$ clock. You **must** replace them with the exact hex values generated by your CubeMX configuration).*

### 2. Implement the Driver Function
Place this implementation in your `MLX90640_I2C_Driver.cpp` (or wherever your `MLX90640_I2CRead` and `Write` functions are defined):

```cpp
#include "MLX90640_I2C_Driver.h"
#include "stm32l4xx_hal.h"

// Extern your I2C handles so the driver can use them
extern I2C_HandleTypeDef hi2c1;
extern I2C_HandleTypeDef hi2c2;

// Pointer to keep track of the currently active bus (if you switch between them)
extern I2C_HandleTypeDef* active_i2c_bus; 

// REPLACE THESE with your actual CubeMX TIMINGR values!
#define TIMINGR_400KHZ  0x10D1143A  // Example for 400kHz @ 80MHz
#define TIMINGR_1000KHZ 0x0080216C  // Example for 1MHz @ 80MHz

void MLX90640_I2CFreqSet(int freq) {
    uint32_t new_timing = 0;

    // 1. Determine the target Timing register value
    if (freq == 400) {
        new_timing = TIMINGR_400KHZ;
    } 
    else if (freq == 1000) {
        new_timing = TIMINGR_1000KHZ;
    }
    else {
        return; // Unsupported frequency, do nothing
    }

    // Only re-initialize if the timing is actually changing to save CPU cycles
    if (active_i2c_bus->Init.Timing != new_timing) {
        
        // 2. De-initialize the I2C peripheral
        HAL_I2C_DeInit(active_i2c_bus);

        // 3. Update the timing value
        active_i2c_bus->Init.Timing = new_timing;

        // 4. Important for 1 MHz: Enable Fast Mode Plus if switching to 1000 kHz
        // Note: The specific macro depends on your I2C pins (e.g., I2C1, I2C2)
        if (freq == 1000) {
            if (active_i2c_bus == &hi2c1) {
                HAL_I2CEx_EnableFastModePlus(I2C_FASTMODEPLUS_I2C1);
            } else if (active_i2c_bus == &hi2c2) {
                HAL_I2CEx_EnableFastModePlus(I2C_FASTMODEPLUS_I2C2);
            }
        } else {
             if (active_i2c_bus == &hi2c1) {
                HAL_I2CEx_DisableFastModePlus(I2C_FASTMODEPLUS_I2C1);
            } else if (active_i2c_bus == &hi2c2) {
                HAL_I2CEx_DisableFastModePlus(I2C_FASTMODEPLUS_I2C2);
            }
        }

        // 5. Re-initialize the I2C peripheral with the new speed
        HAL_I2C_Init(active_i2c_bus);
    }
}
```

### 3. Critical STM32 Hardware Details
* **Fast Mode Plus (FM+) Drive:** To reach 1 MHz, the STM32 hardware requires stronger GPIO pin driving capabilities. The `HAL_I2CEx_EnableFastModePlus()` function connects the internal SYSCFG registers to boost the sink current capability of the $I^2C$ pins to 20mA. 
* **Pull-up Resistors:** For 1 MHz ($I^2C$ Fast Mode Plus), the standard internal pull-up resistors of the STM32 (~40k$\Omega$) are too weak. You **must** use external pull-up resistors on SDA and SCL. A typical value for 1 MHz is between $1\text{k}\Omega$ and $2.2\text{k}\Omega$, depending on your bus capacitance.
